      },
      "date": "2012-03-03 10:17:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.2/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/6c3dda2a-6518-11e1-ac48-5254004bbbd3).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "53bc1e430225fdc222b8a0d22fc215a48f98909d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-06 20:51:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI think that the cleanup needs to be kept separate from the fix for this bug.  I'm sick at the moment, so maybe I'm not at my best, but it is not at all clear to me why we need separate _rcu named list handling functions.\n\nIt is not clear that this addresses the basic bug either which is this:  if there are 1 million locks outstanding, D_INFO will hang for a long time printing information for 1 million locks to the log.  Unless I am mistaken, this patch makes the info printed for the individual locks less, but does not address the problem of the list being very very long.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "8c281fcc9faf58e669136791fca0d2739bd4b6a3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-06 20:51:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "034286eb0344a80f539d0a8fa5a84566098d1a49",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2012-03-07 01:08:00.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nChris, yes if there are 1 million locks, they will be dumped, but in this period no lock is held, and it will be done on one specific CPU core, so other ldlm threads won't be blocked, and system won't be unresponsive.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "68596e9650decc2c283aa31cb16e825b0e1d982f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-03-09 12:56:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThis patch looks good to me. However, it may be conflicted with http://review.whamcloud.com/#change,2074 and one of you guys have to fix your patch, so you have to be quicker ;-).\n\nI tend to think it may not be good to dump all locks in ldlm_lock_enqueue(), what if we dump all lock only when error occurs?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
